[/asy] We drop an altitude from $C$ to $AE$, and we let $F$ be the foot of this altitude: [asy]
pair A,B,C,D,E,F;
A=(0,0);
B=(1,0);
C=(1+sqrt(2)/2,sqrt(2)/2);
D=(1+sqrt(2)/2,3sqrt(2)/2);
E=(1,2+sqrt(2));
F=(1,1+sqrt(2)/2);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--A);
draw(C--A--D);
draw(C--F);
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,NE);
label("$D$",D,N);
label("$E$",E,N);
label("$F$",F,E);
label("$2$",(C+D)/2,E);
label("$2$",(B+C)/2,S);
label("$2$",(D+E)/2,N);
label("$x$",(A+F)/2,NE);
label("$x$",(F+E)/2,NE);
[/asy] Then $\triangle CFA$ and $\triangle CFE$ are similar, so $\frac{CE}{CA} = \frac{CF}{CE}$, or $CE^2 = CA \cdot CF$.  Since $CA = x+2$ and $CF = x$, we have \[CE^2 = x(x+2).\]From $\triangle CDE$, we have $DE^2 = CD^2 - CE^2 = 2^2 - CE^2$, so \[AE^2 = AD^2 + DE^2 = 2^2 + (x+2)^2 - CE^2.\]Substituting $CE^2 = x(x+2)$, we get \[AE^2 = 8 + x^2 + 4x - x(x+2) = 8 + x^2 + 4x - x^2 - 2x = 8 + 2x.\]Thus, $a+b = 8+2=\boxed{10}$.
